        <body>
            <p>The aim of the text is to analyse the extent to which cross-border practices have influenced border demographic dynamics. The authors aim to make a new contribution to the academic debate that will enrich critical reflection and debate on the issue of depopulation, with a view to proposing recommendations for economic policy, within a framework of cross-border institutional cooperation and inter- and intra-governmental coordination.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This is a very interesting topic.&#x00a0;I would like to briefly give a few hints that could help to improve the text and make it more understandable for the readers.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Since the authors consider their text as a research article, I would recommend structuring the text in this sense, starting with a conceptual framework, a literature review, a research question and a hypothesis.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Overall, the article is structured in two parts: 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The first part is a descriptive analysis of the evolution of population indicators over the period 1960-2020. The data is well presented, but I miss a literature review on the topic. Furthermore It should be clearer why the authors choose these indicators and this time frame. The authors should include a rational on the territorial unit of analysis: NUTS 3; two large sections border territories, or NUTS II; the authors should explain in more detail why they chose these different territorial units, This is particularly important for a clear comparison.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Regarding the results of the first part, the collapse of the population in Spanish border municipalities in the period 1960-2020 is very evident, but has been highlighted by several studies, the question would be whether there are specific characteristics of the border regions? If so, the authors should compare this finding with the situation in other Spanish regions. The same would be useful for Portugal. It would make sense to establish two categories "border regions" and "non-border regions". If border regions are more affected by depopulation than "non-border regions", it would give a strong motivation to analyse cross-border cooperation.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The authors claim that the Portuguese part of the Raya Centro-Norte is resisting the depopulation pressure better than the Spanish part, they should present some more evidence of this.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The authors argue that there is a Portuguese strategy for urban or pseudo-urban border areas, either to "anchor" the population, but there is no reference to this strategy. It should be clarified whether this national strategy is only for one local entity, or why it does not work for the rest of the units. There may also have been several strategies on the Spanish side, why did they not work, why were former INTERREG programmes not successful?</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>It should be clarified why the INE data have been supplemented with the database of institutes specialised in territorial statistics. The same for the Portuguese National Statistical Institute.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>In summary, the authors could elaborate on the specific characteristics of border regions and their research methodology.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The second part starts with a theoretical framework, this should be at the beginning and linked to the study on depopulation. The second part should be more concentrated on the question of what CBC means for the problem of depopulation. Especially regarding the Castilla y Le&#x00f3;n-Central Portugal Work Community and Castilla y Le&#x00f3;n-North Portugal Work Community (NORCYL). The authors should increase the empirical evidence of the CBS in relation to cross border regions, .e.g. evolution of the budget &#x2026;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The authors mentioned the concepts of multi-level system, Europe of regions and Euroregions, there should be a better definition of these concepts, it may become clear that there are important conceptual differences between these terms.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The first analysis is based on nuts 3 the second part concentrated on nuts 2, the discussion should include a few words on the implications of this fact for the comparison.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>In general terms both parts - a descriptive analysis of the population situation in the municipalities of the North-Central Spanish-Portuguese border and the descriptive analysis of institutional coordination in cross-border areas - should be better connected.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Above all, the interrelationship between population and CBC should be made clearer. The author could also include some economic policy recommendations, as mentioned in the introduction.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The text would benefit from a linguistic revision, some expression should be more precise:</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>&#x201c;It is never easy to compare Spain and Portugal, even though there are so many similarities (EU members, shared past, joint future, etc.)&#x201d;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>&#x201c;In short, the necessary cocktail for a &#x2018;better&#x2019; life that, on the one hand, &#x2018;retains&#x2019; the current residents, preventing them from abandoning the territory and, on the other, &#x2018;attracts&#x2019; the older population to these &#x2018;urban functionality&#x2019; areas. young and ready.&#x201d;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>&#x201c;This bet of the Portuguese State for the border urban or pseudo-urban areas [&#x2026;].&#x201c;</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list>
